definition.value: A benzoate ester that is an ester of 4-hydroxybenzoic acid.
A tetramethoxyflavone that is  tangeretin in which the methoxy group at position 5 has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A glycosyloxyisoflavone that is  daidzein substituted by a 6-O-(carboxyacetyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A  glycosyloxyisoflavone that is genistin in which the hydroxy hydrogen at position 6'' has been replaced by a malonyl group.
A glycosyloxyisoflavone that is isoflavone substituted by a methoxy group at position 6, a hydroxy group at position 4' and a  beta-D-glucopyranosyloxy group at position 7.
A glycosyloxyisoflavone that is glycitin substituted by a  malonyl group at position 6''.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): colour retention agent.
An aryl beta-D-glucoside that is  phloretin attached to a  beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 2' via a glycosidic linkage.
A proanthocyanidin isolated from Cinnamomum cassia.
A dimethoxyflavone that is flavone substituted by methoxy groups at positions 6 and 7 and hydroxy groups at positions 5 and 4' respectively.

A sesquiterpenoid that is 4,4a,5,6,7,8-hexahydronaphthalen-2(3H)-one which is substituted by methyl groups at positions 4 and 4a, and by an isopropenyl group at position 6 (the 4R,4aS,6R stereoisomer).
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): preservative.
A potassium salt that is the monopotassium salt of carbonic acid. It has fungicidal properties and is used in organic farming for the control of powdery mildew and apple scab.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, stabilizer.
The all-trans-isomer of phytoene.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): colour.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): sweetener.
A mixture resulting from extraction from propolis.
A mixture of sugar (fructose, glucose, sucrose) and carbohydrate components that is a by-product from sugar refinery.
LanguaL term definition: Liquid product remaining after crystallization of sugar from sugar syrup; most molasses is made from sugar cane.
Any member of the class of  xanthones having one or more glycosyl residues attached at unspecified positions.
A sulfamate ester that is 1,2,3-oxathiazin-4(3H)-one 2,2-dioxide substituted by a methyl group at position 6.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): flavour enhancer, sweetener.
A dipeptide composed of N-(3,3-dimethylbutyl)-L-aspartic acid and methyl L-phenylalanate units joined by a peptide linkage.

LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): flavour enhancer, sweetener.


Neotame is an artificial sweetener made by NutraSweet that is between 7,000 and 13,000 times as sweet as sucrose (table sugar). Neotame was approved by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for general use in July 2002, and has now been approved by the EU to become a classified E number (E961), but it is not yet widely used in food products. Neotame also is approved for use in Australia and New Zealand. It is assigned the International Numbering System (INS) food additive code 961.
A gallate ester obtained by condensation of the carboxy group of gallic acid with the hydroxy group of octanol.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): antioxidant.
Any derivative of a proteinogenic amino acid resulting from reaction at an amino group, carboxy group, or a side-chain functional group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen by a heteroatom.

Any of the 23 alpha-amino acids that are precursors to proteins, and are incorporated into proteins during translation. The group includes the 20 amino acids encoded by the nuclear genes of eukaryotes together with selenocysteine, pyrrolysine, and N-formylmethionine. Apart from glycine, which is non-chiral, all have L configuration.
Any amino-acid that is not naturally encoded in the genetic code of any organism.

Any derivative of an amino acid resulting from reaction at an amino group, carboxy group, side-chain functional group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing amino acid residues.

A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-glutamic acid at the amino group or either of the carboxy groups, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-glutamic acid by a heteroatom.
Any stilbenol that is the monosulfate derivative of resveratrol.
Any phospho sugar that is the phosphate derivative of pentose.
A linear dextrin or short chained amylose (DP 20-30) that can be produced by enzymatic hydrolysis of the alpha-1,6 glycosidic bonds or debranching amylopectin.
A xi-progoitrin(1-) that is the conjugate base of progoitrin.
An organic sodium salt having D-gluconate as the counterion.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): sequestrant, stabilizer, thickener.
A 4-hydroxybenzoate ester in which the esterifying alcohol is an alkanol (in diagram, R = alkyl). Commonly used as preservatives in cosmetic and pharmaceutical products.
A polysaccharide acid oxoanion produced by bacteria, which is used as a substitute for agar as gelling agent in various clinical bacteriological media.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): stabilizer, thickener.
An amino-acid betaine that is trans-4-hydroxy-L-proline zwitterion in which both of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen have been replaced by methyl groups.
A bismuth cation having a net electric charge of +3.
A hydroxyisoflavone that is  genistein  in which the hydroxy group at position 7 is replaced by a methoxy group.
A hydrate that is the decahydrate form of disodium tetraborate.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive.
